        After spinoff, Edgewell CEO eyes global growth, acquisitions
    


By Lisa Brown St. Louis Post-Dispatch  











Lisa Brown


























Jul 12, 2015

 (…)
































                    +1 











Corporate logo for Edgewell Personal Care.



















David Hatfield, CEO of Edgewell Personal Care

































































St. Louis this month gained a new public company and a new corporate name with the successful split of Energizer Holdings into two consumer products giants.The company that kept the Energizer name is focused on batteries and lighting products, and remains based in Town and Country.The other, Edgewell Personal Care, took over more than two dozen consumer brands, many sold around the globe, including Schick razors, Banana Boat sunscreen and Wet Ones hand wipes. That portfolio of personal care brands generated $2.6 billion in sales last year.
Based in Chesterfield, Edgewell employs 6,000 people, including 175 locally.David Hatfield, the new chief executive of Edgewell, took a moment last week to reflect on the massive, yearlong undertaking that created two companies, and the strategy that will guide his company going forward.Most spinoffs involve only a small fraction of a company, Hatfield said in an interview. But the separation of Energizer’s household and personal care divisions was nearly a 50-50 split, ratcheting up the complexity of the task.“We divided a company across 50-plus countries,” he said. “Folks have done a superb job, and we’re looking forward to a new beginning.”Hatfield didn’t stop to ruminate on the past for long, however. Edgewell is putting a bigger priority on international growth than it did previously, he said, and the company is investing heavily in innovation to develop new products. Acquisitions — a critical part of the company’s prior growth — will help propel the company’s global growth, he added.Hatfield started at Eveready’s battery division in 1988, 12 years before Energizer and the Eveready brand were spun off from Ralston Purina Co. During his career, he helped oversee several major acquisitions as Energizer diversified beyond its battery base, including purchasing the Schick-Wilkinson Sword razor business in 2003 for $930 million and the $1.9 billion acquisition of Playtex Products in 2007.
With the battery division now a separate company, Edgewell can focus on its core business, personal care products, Hatfield said.“We compete in attractive categories and we have strong brands,” he said.In addition to Schick razors and Edge and Skintimate shaving preparation products that account for 61 percent of Edgewell’s sales, Edgewell’s brands include Hawaiian Tropic sunscreen, and Playtex and o.b. tampons. Feminine care and sun/skin care each account for about 16 percent of sales, with infant and other products totaling 7 percent of sales.
“We’ve been built through acquisitions over time,” Hatfield said. “We have a legacy of disciplined M&A and we look to continue that going forward. Our philosophy is we look to stay close to our core. We’re going to look at businesses in categories we compete in, particularly in suncare, and adjacencies such as skin care and grooming.”RAZOR FOCUSWith razors and shaving prep products accounting for more than half of its business, the segment is Edgewell’s No. 1 focus, Hatfield said. Edgewell’s wet shave net sales totaled $1.6 billion in fiscal 2014, with 45 percent of sales in North America, 28 percent in Europe, 19 percent in Asia and 8 percent in Latin America.“Management will be relying on increased investment behind the growth brands, innovation, leveraging of the entire portfolio (including private label), and international expansion, particularly in developing markets,” John Faucher, a J.P. Morgan analyst, wrote in a recent research note. Procter & Gamble’s Gillette is the market leader for razors in the U.S., followed by Edgewell’s Schick brand. Both Gillette and Schick face increasing competition from Harry’s and Dollar Shave Club, which are growing their online razor sales.Hatfield said he’s watching the online competitors closely.“That’s an interesting phenomenon that we have to watch,” he said, adding that most online competitors aren’t profitable and are burning through cash.If the online competitors survive, Hatfield said Edgewell’s private label razor business could act as suppliers. “We’re positioned well to help them,” he said.



